---
import BaseLayout from "@layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { SITE } from "@utils/constants";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="AI Partnership"
  description="A strategic collaboration between AI tools and operational expertise — integrating intelligent automation into real workflows to scale execution faster, without handing over the judgment."
>
  <!-- Page Header -->
  <section class="ai-header" aria-labelledby="ai-heading">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="ai-eyebrow">AI Partnership</p>
      <h1 id="ai-heading">Strategic AI Integration</h1>
      <p class="ai-intro">
        A strategic collaboration between AI tools and my own skills, knowledge, and experience — built to integrate intelligent automation into real operational workflows and scale execution faster, without ever handing over the judgment.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Why I Work This Way -->
  <section class="ai-section" aria-labelledby="why-heading">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="prose-block">
        <h2 id="why-heading">Why I Work This Way</h2>
        <p>
          I don't see AI as a shortcut — I see it as a force multiplier for people who already know how to think. Every tool I've adopted in my career, from SAP ERP to Salesforce CRM, existed to remove friction between a good decision and the action that follows it. AI is the newest version of that same idea, and it's the most powerful one yet.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- How I Use It -->
  <section class="ai-section alt-section" aria-labelledby="how-heading">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="prose-block">
        <h2 id="how-heading">How I Use It</h2>

        <div class="use-case">
          <h3>In my daily operations work</h3>
          <p>
            I use AI-driven workflows inside Salesforce CRM to turn raw pipeline data into forecasts my leadership team can act on same-day, not next-week. What used to take a manual pull-and-reformat cycle now takes minutes — freeing my time for the judgment calls a dashboard can't make: which distributor relationship needs a phone call today, which quote is at risk, which trend is worth escalating before it becomes a problem.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="use-case">
          <h3>In my function as a sales enabler</h3>
          <p>
            I use AI to give distributors and reps the tools to move faster without me in the middle of every step — building quick-turn quote templates, order-status summaries, and distributor-facing materials that used to take me hours to draft by hand. Earlier in my career, I standardized our quote workflow the traditional way and cut response time by 50% and order errors by 60%; today, AI is the tool I'd reach for first to get to that same kind of result faster. That's the core of sales enablement to me: removing friction for the people actually closing the deal, while I stay focused on the relationships and judgment calls that keep the pipeline healthy.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="use-case">
          <h3>In training and onboarding</h3>
          <p>
            I use AI to build the materials that get people productive faster. When I coached and onboarded new team members on corporate standards at Cree Lighting, the bottleneck was never the training content — it was how long it took to produce clear, consistent materials tailored to people ramping up at different speeds and experience levels. AI compresses that production time significantly, so the training session itself can focus entirely on application, questions, and hands-on practice rather than on content delivery.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="use-case">
          <h3>In building KPI frameworks</h3>
          <p>
            I use AI to turn scattered data into the dashboards leadership actually looks at. When I built and shipped a Salesforce CRM pipeline dashboard that got adopted company-wide, the hard part was never pulling the numbers — it was deciding which KPIs actually mattered, how to frame them so a distributor issue surfaced before it became a crisis, and how to keep the dashboard simple enough that people opened it daily instead of ignoring it. AI helps me build and iterate on that structure fast. Choosing what to measure, and what a number should trigger, is still mine to decide.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="use-case">
          <h3>In building my own career tools</h3>
          <p>
            I used Claude Code — an AI coding assistant — to independently design, build, and deploy this portfolio site from scratch. I'm not a software engineer. I didn't need to become one. I needed to be someone who could direct a capable tool with clarity, review its output critically, and ship something real. That's the same skill set I bring to cross-functional operations: I don't need to be the expert in every system to own the outcome — I need to know what "done well" looks like and hold the work to that standard.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="use-case">
          <h3>In my own professional development</h3>
          <p>
            I use AI as a thinking partner — to stress-test a strategy before I present it, to model a financial scenario before I commit to it, to sharpen a piece of writing before it goes out under my name. The judgment is always mine. The tool just means I iterate faster and arrive at a better version, sooner.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- My Point of View -->
  <section class="ai-section" aria-labelledby="pov-heading">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="prose-block">
        <h2 id="pov-heading">My Point of View</h2>
        <p>
          AI doesn't replace operational discipline — it raises the floor on what "good" looks like, and it raises the ceiling on how fast a small, focused person can move. The people who get the most value from it aren't the ones who let it think for them. They're the ones who already had strong judgment and just needed less friction between having an idea and executing it well.
        </p>
        <p>
          I'm also honest about the limits. AI is only as useful as the clarity of what you ask it to do, and it doesn't replace the relationship work — the phone call to an anxious distributor, the trust built over years with a partner in a market three time zones away. It handles the parts of the job that used to eat the hours I needed for the parts only a person can do.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Results -->
  <section class="ai-section alt-section" aria-labelledby="results-heading">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="prose-block">
        <h2 id="results-heading">Results I've Seen in My Own Career</h2>
        <ul class="results-list">
          <li>
            <strong>Standardized workflows</strong> that cut quote response time by 50% and order errors by 60% — built on the same principle of using the right tool to remove friction from a process, not just work harder inside a broken one.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>A live portfolio site</strong>, built and shipped independently using AI-assisted development, that lets me show — not just tell — how I execute when I own something end-to-end.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Faster, sharper decision cycles</strong> in day-to-day operations, because AI-driven CRM workflows give me real-time visibility instead of last week's numbers.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Figure 1 -->
  <section class="ai-section figure-section">
    <div class="container">
      <figure class="ai-figure">
        <img
          src={`${SITE.base}/assets/ai_vs_human_sales_framework.svg`}
          alt="Framework comparing what AI does versus what I decide in sales"
          class="ai-figure-img"
        />
        <figcaption>
          Statistic source:
          <a
            href="https://www.salesforce.com/sales/state-of-sales/sales-statistics/"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener noreferrer"
          >
            Salesforce, State of Sales Report, 2026
          </a>
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The Real Benefit -->
  <section class="ai-section" aria-labelledby="benefit-heading">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="prose-block">
        <h2 id="benefit-heading">The Real Benefit: Humans Still Decide</h2>
        <p>
          I want to be direct about something, because I think it matters more than any tool list: <strong>AI doesn't make the call. I do — and so does my team, and my leadership.</strong> The decision, the accountability, and the judgment stay human, every time.
        </p>
        <p>So what's the real benefit, if AI isn't deciding anything?</p>

        <div class="benefit-grid">
          <div class="benefit-item">
            <h3>Compresses the time between "I don't know" and "I know enough to decide"</h3>
            <p>AI can scan thousands of rows of data and flag an anomaly in 30 seconds. I still decide what to do about it — but without AI, I would have spent two hours just finding it.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="benefit-item">
            <h3>Lowers the cost of exploring before committing</h3>
            <p>Modeling three different scenarios in Excel used to take an afternoon. Now I can test five in twenty minutes and decide with more information, not more time pressure.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="benefit-item">
            <h3>Frees up human bandwidth for the part no machine can do</h3>
            <p>Every hour AI saves me on preparing a report is an hour I get back for the work that actually requires a person: reading the room, negotiating with a distributor, weighing a trade-off with context a model simply doesn't have access to.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="benefit-item">
            <h3>Democratizes analysis without requiring a data science team</h3>
            <p>I'm not a data analyst by training — but with tools like Copilot in Excel or Claude, I can ask my own data direct questions instead of waiting in another team's queue.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="closing-statement">
          AI doesn't make the call — it makes sure I'm making the call with better information, faster. The decision, the accountability, and the judgment stay human. Every time.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Figure 2 -->
  <section class="ai-section figure-section alt-section">
    <div class="container">
      <figure class="ai-figure">
        <img
          src={`${SITE.base}/assets/ai_vs_human_decision_framework_cited.svg`}
          alt="Framework comparing what AI does versus what I decide"
          class="ai-figure-img"
        />
        <figcaption>
          Statistic source:
          <a
            href="https://www.deloitte.com/us/en/insights/topics/talent/human-capital-trends/2026/decision-making-with-ai.html"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener noreferrer"
          >
            Deloitte Insights, 2026 Global Human Capital Trends
          </a>
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Cross-Functional -->
  <section class="ai-section" aria-labelledby="collab-heading">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="prose-block">
        <h2 id="collab-heading">The One Skill AI Cannot Touch: Cross-Functional Collaboration</h2>
        <p>
          There's a skill sitting underneath everything I've described above, and it's the one I'd defend the hardest: the ability to show up, build trust across teams, and get people who don't naturally align to row in the same direction. No AI tool books the room, reads the tension between two department heads who disagree, or earns a distributor's confidence after a bad quarter. That's not a data problem. It's a human one.
        </p>
        <p>
          I've built my entire career on this skill. "Cross-functional program ownership" isn't a buzzword on my resume — it's what I actually do: sit between sales, operations, IT, and leadership, and make sure the handoffs don't drop. AI can hand me the data those teams need to align around. It cannot replace the conversation, the timing, or the trust required to actually get them aligned.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is also, I think, the most undervalued skill in the AI conversation right now. Everyone's talking about what AI can automate. Almost no one is talking about the fact that the more AI handles the busywork, the more valuable the person who can still walk into a room and get five different stakeholders to agree becomes — because that skill was never about the busywork to begin with.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Figure 3 -->
  <section class="ai-section figure-section">
    <div class="container">
      <figure class="ai-figure">
        <img
          src={`${SITE.base}/assets/ai_vs_human_pm_framework.svg`}
          alt="Framework comparing what AI does versus what I decide in project management"
          class="ai-figure-img"
        />
        <figcaption>
          Statistic source:
          <a
            href="https://www.pmi.org/learning/thought-leadership/shaping-the-future-of-project-management-with-ai"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener noreferrer"
          >
            PMI, Shaping the Future of Project Management With AI
          </a>
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Generative AI in Practice -->
  <section class="ai-section alt-section" aria-labelledby="genai-heading">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="prose-block">
        <h2 id="genai-heading">Generative AI in Practice: Prompting and Workflow Efficiency</h2>
        <p>
          I don't just use generative AI tools — I've built a discipline around getting reliable output from them, which is a different skill than simply typing a request and taking whatever comes back.
        </p>

        <div class="use-case">
          <h3>Effective prompting, in practice</h3>
          <p>
            When I built this portfolio site using Claude Code, I didn't get a usable result on the first attempt — I got there by being specific about structure, tone, and constraints, then reviewing the output and refining the instructions each round until it matched what I actually needed. That iterative loop — instruct, review, refine — is the same discipline I apply anywhere I use generative AI: the quality of what comes out depends entirely on the clarity of what goes in.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="use-case">
          <h3>Workflow efficiency, in practice</h3>
          <p>
            The same instruct-review-refine approach applies to the reports and materials I produce day to day — status updates, distributor communications, training documents. I don't accept the first draft AI gives me at face value; I validate it against what I actually know about the account, the market, or the situation before it goes out. The efficiency gain isn't skipping that review step — it's that the first draft now takes minutes instead of an hour, so more of my time goes into the judgment call, not the formatting.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Closing -->
  <section class="ai-section closing-section" aria-labelledby="closing-heading">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="closing-block">
        <p>
          I'm looking for the next place to apply this the same way: using every tool available — AI included — to move fast, stay accountable for the outcome, and never mistake "busy" for "effective."
        </p>
        <a href={`${SITE.base}/contact`} class="btn btn-primary">
          Schedule a Strategic Conversation
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  /* ── Page Header ── */
  .ai-header {
    padding-block: var(--space-20);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-alt);
    border-bottom: var(--border-width) solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .ai-eyebrow {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    font-weight: var(--weight-semibold);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    color: #c89b3c;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
  }

  .ai-header h1 {
    font-size: var(--text-4xl);
    font-weight: var(--weight-bold);
    line-height: var(--leading-tight);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-6);
  }

  .ai-intro {
    font-size: var(--text-xl);
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);
    max-width: 48rem;
    font-style: italic;
  }

  /* ── Sections ── */
  .ai-section {
    padding-block: var(--space-12);
    border-bottom: var(--border-width) solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .ai-section:last-child {
    border-bottom: none;
  }

  .alt-section {
    background-color: var(--color-bg-alt);
  }

  /* ── Prose block ── */
  .prose-block {
    max-width: 52rem;
  }

  .prose-block h2 {
    font-size: var(--text-2xl);
    font-weight: var(--weight-bold);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-5);
    color: var(--color-text);
  }

  .prose-block p {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
  }

  .prose-block p:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  .prose-block strong {
    color: var(--color-text);
    font-weight: var(--weight-semibold);
  }

  /* ── Use cases ── */
  .use-case {
    margin-top: var(--space-8);
    padding-left: var(--space-5);
    border-left: 2px solid #c89b3c;
  }

  .use-case h3 {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    font-weight: var(--weight-semibold);
    color: var(--color-text);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .use-case p {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  /* ── Results list ── */
  .results-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin-top: var(--space-5);
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-5);
  }

  .results-list li {
    position: relative;
    padding: var(--space-5) var(--space-6);
    background-color: var(--color-surface);
    border: var(--border-width) solid var(--color-border);
    border-left: 3px solid #c89b3c;
    border-radius: var(--radius-md);
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);
  }

  .results-list li + li {
    margin-top: 0;
  }

  /* ── Benefit grid ── */
  .benefit-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(min(100%, 22rem), 1fr));
    gap: var(--space-5);
    margin-top: var(--space-8);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-8);
  }

  .benefit-item {
    padding: var(--space-6);
    background-color: var(--color-surface);
    border: var(--border-width) solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--radius-lg);
  }

  .benefit-item h3 {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    font-weight: var(--weight-semibold);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: var(--leading-normal);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
  }

  .benefit-item p {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  .closing-statement {
    font-size: var(--text-lg) !important;
    color: var(--color-text) !important;
    font-weight: var(--weight-medium);
    padding: var(--space-6);
    border-top: var(--border-width) solid var(--color-border);
    margin-top: var(--space-4);
  }

  /* ── Figures ── */
  .figure-section {
    padding-block: var(--space-10);
  }

  .ai-figure {
    margin: 0;
  }

  .ai-figure-img {
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 640px;
    height: auto;
    border-radius: var(--radius-lg);
    border: var(--border-width) solid var(--color-border);
    display: block;
  }

  .ai-figure figcaption {
    margin-top: var(--space-3);
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    line-height: var(--leading-normal);
  }

  .ai-figure figcaption a {
    color: #7fa8d9;
    text-decoration-color: transparent;
    transition: text-decoration-color var(--transition-fast);
  }

  .ai-figure figcaption a:hover {
    color: #7fa8d9;
    text-decoration-color: #7fa8d9;
  }

  /* ── Closing ── */
  .closing-section {
    background-color: var(--color-bg-alt);
  }

  .closing-block {
    max-width: 48rem;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-8);
  }

  .closing-block p {
    font-size: var(--text-xl);
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);
    font-style: italic;
  }

  @media (max-width: 640px) {
    .ai-header {
      padding-block: var(--space-12);
    }

    .use-case {
      padding-left: var(--space-4);
    }
  }
</style>
